|[[Carlisle Indian Industrial School|Carlisle Indian]] ||5'11\" ||184||24\n|-\n| ||Dewey Scarboro||Halfback|| 0||[[Moultrie, Georgia]]||Moultrie High School ||5'6\" ||145 ||19\n|-\n| ||Wally Smith||Halfback||0  ||Atlanta, Georgia|| ||5'6\"||154||21\n|}\n\n====Unlisted====\n*L. M. Lamar\n<ref name=dope>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3553262/the_atlanta_constitution/|work=Atlanta Constitution|title=Georgia Tech's 1918  Team; The Dope at a Glance|date=October 13, 1918|page=5|accessdate=May 4, 2016|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref name=yearbp/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/geot/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/lettermen01.pdf|title=Letterwinners|publisher=Georgia Institute of Technology|accessdate=August 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Scoring leaders===\nThe following is an incomplete list of statistics and scores, largely dependent on newspaper summaries.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets|Player | Touchdowns|Extra points |Points}}\n|-\n|[[Red Barron]]||15 || || 90\n|-\n|[[Bill Fincher]]||2||56 || 68\n|-\n|Pug Allen||10|| || 60\n|-\n|Frank Ferst||10|| || 60\n|-\n|[[Buck Flowers]]||7||2 ||44\n|-\n|Wally Smith||7|| || 42\n|-\n|B. Adams||4|| || 24\n|-\n|F. R. Cobb||4|| || 24\n|-\n|[[Joe Guyon]]||4|| ||  24\n|-\n|[[Albert Staton]]||4|| ||24\n|-\n|Shorty Doyal||1|| || 6\n|-\n! Total!!68!!58!!466\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==Endnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|last=Powers|first=Francis J. |year=1969|title= Life Story of Glen S. (Pop) Warner, Gridiron's Greatest Strategist|location=Chicago, IL|publisher= The Athletic Institute|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tfMjFXHLfZwC&pg=PT147#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=100 Things Yellow Jackets Fans Should Know and Do Before They Die|last1=Van Brimmer | first1=Adam | last2=Rice | first2=Homer |date=2011|location=Chicago|publisher=Triumph Books|isbn=978-1-61749-703-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=A History of Southern Football 1890\u20131928|last=Woodruff|first=Fuzzy|volume=2|year=1928|ref=harv}}\n\n{{Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football navbox}}\n{{SIAA football champions}}\n\n[[Category:1918 Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Association football season|Georgia Tech]]\n[[Category:Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football seasons]]\n[[Category:1918 in sports in Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia Tech Golden Tornado football]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n |year = 1918\n |team = Georgia Tech Golden Tornado\n |sport = football\n |image = 18gatech.jpg\n |image_size = 290\n |caption = \n |conference = Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Association\n |short_conf = SIAA\n |record = 6\u20131\n |conf_record = 3\u20130\n |head_coach = [[John Heisman]]\n |hc_year = 15th\n |off_scheme = [[Jump shift]]\n |def_scheme = \n |captain = [[Bill Fincher]]\n |stadium = [[Bobby Dodd Stadium|Grant Field]]\n |champion = SIAA champion\n}}\n{{1918 SIAA football standings}}\nThe '''1918 Georgia Tech Golden Tornado football team'''{{refn|group=note|Although Georgia Tech's teams are officially known as the \"Yellow Jackets\", northern writers called the team the \"Golden Tornado\" in 1917; the name was commonly used until 1928 and for many years afterwards as an alternate nickname.<ref>{{Harvnb|Van Brimmer|Rice|2011|p=147}}</ref>}} represented the [[Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football|Georgia Tech Golden Tornado]] of the [[Georgia Institute of Technology]] during the [[1918 Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Association football season]]. The Tornado was coached by [[John Heisman]] in his 15th year as head coach, compiling a record of 6\u20131 (3\u20130 SIAA) and outscoring opponents 466 to 32. Georgia Tech played its home games at [[Bobby Dodd Stadium|Grant Field]].\n\nTech eclipsed 100 points three different times. Its only road game was its only loss to [[College football national championships in NCAA Division I FBS|national champion]] [[1918 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|Pittsburgh]] at [[Forbes Field]]. Pittsburgh was the only team to score on Tech during the 1918 season. The defeat ended Georgia Tech's 33-game winning streak.\n\n[[Center (American football)|Center]] [[Bum Day]] was recognized as a consensus first-team [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]]. He was a first-team selection by [[Walter Camp]]; the first [[Southern United States|Southerner]] to be chosen for Camp's  All-America first team. [[Bill Fincher]] and [[Joe Guyon]] also made consensus All-America. Fincher and [[Buck Flowers]] made Camp's second-team.\n\n==Before the season==\nBecause of [[American entry into World War I|America's entry into World War I]] in April 1917 and the ongoing war effort, several SIAA schools did not field football teams in 1918.<ref>{{Harvnb|Woodruff|1928|page=70}}</ref> Coming off the South's first national championship in [[1917 Georgia Tech Golden Tornado football team|1917]], Tech lost several players to the war effort and was heavily reliant on freshmen.<ref name=dope/>\n[[File:Bill Fincher.jpg|thumb|left|120px|Bill Fincher]]\nWith captain-elect [[Everett Strupper]] lost to the war effort, [[Tackle (gridiron football position)|tackle]] and [[placekicker]] [[Bill Fincher]] was left as captain.<ref name=opening/> Fincher had a [[glass eye]] which he would covertly pull out after feigning an injury, turn to his opponents and say: \"So that's how you want to play!\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cm1TZA6jCSgC&pg=PA28&lpg=PA28&dq=bill+fincher+glass+eye#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=SEC Football: 75 Years of Pride and Passion|author=Richard Scott|page=28|isbn=978-1-61673-133-5|date=2008-09-15}}</ref>\n\nCoach [[John Heisman]] used the pre-[[Snap (gridiron football)|snap]] movement of his \"[[jump shift]]\" offense.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/footballimmortal00weya|url-access=registration|title=Football immortals|publisher=Macmillan|page=[https://archive.org/details/footballimmortal00weya/page/n126 91]|author=Alexander M. Weyand|year=1962}}</ref> Former [[End (American football)|end]] and [[University of Notre Dame|Notre Dame]] alumnus [[Fay Wood]] assisted Heisman as [[Lineman (gridiron football)|line]] coach.<ref name=yearbp/>\n\n[[Buck Flowers]] was in his first year on the team. He was a small [[backfield|back]] who had transferred from [[Davidson College|Davidson]], where last year he starred in the game against Tech. Flowers had grown to weigh 150 pounds and was a backup until Heisman discovered his ability as an open-field runner on punt returns. \"Heisman's eyes bulged. And bulged again. On the first punt, Buck ran through the entire first team. Same thing again&nbsp;... and again. Heisman had uncovered one of the greatest broken-field runners.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Buck Flowers: He Could Do It All \u2014 Well |newspaper=Daily Item|location=Sumter, S.C.|date=October 15, 1969|page=B2|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1979&dat=19691015&id=fXMiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=8qkFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1126,1790436}}</ref>\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 5\n| time = \n| w/l = w\n| opponent = [[1918 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson]]\n| site_stadium = [[Bobby Dodd Stadium|Grant Field]]\n| site_cityst = [[Atlanta|Atlanta, GA]]\n| gamename = [[Clemson\u2013Georgia Tech football rivalry|rivalry]]\n| score = 28\u20130\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 12\n| time = \n| w/l = w\n| opponent = [[1918 Furman Purple Hurricane football team|Furman]]\n| site_stadium = Grant Field\n| site_cityst = Atlanta, GA\n| score = 118\u20130\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 19\n| time = \n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| opponent = 11th Cavalry\n| site_stadium = Grant Field\n| site_cityst = Atlanta, GA\n| score = 123\u20130\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 26\n| time = \n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| opponent = [[1918 Camp Gordon football team|Camp Gordon]]\n| site_stadium = Grant Field\n| site_cityst = Atlanta, GA\n| score = 28\u20130\n| attend = 12,000\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 10\n| time = \n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1918|team=NC State Aggies|title=NC State}}\n| site_stadium = Grant Field\n| site_cityst = Atlanta, GA\n| score = 128\u20130\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 23\n| time = \n| w/l = l\n| nonconf = y\n| away = y\n| opponent = [[1918 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|Pittsburgh]]\n| site_stadium = [[Forbes Field]]\n| site_cityst = [[Pittsburgh|Pittsburgh, PA]]\n| score = 32\u20130\n| attend = 30,000\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 28\n| time = \n| w/l = w\n| opponent = [[1918 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]]\n| site_stadium = Grant Field\n| site_cityst = Atlanta, GA\n| gamename = [[Auburn\u2013Georgia Tech football rivalry|rivalry]]\n| score = 41\u20130\n| attend = \n}}\n}}\n\n==Season summary==\n===Clemson===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Title = '''Clemson at Georgia Tech'''\n| Visitor = Clemson\n| Host = '''Ga. Tech'''\n| V1 = 0| V2 =0| V3 =0| V4 =0\n| H1 = 0| H2 =14| H3 =7| H4 =7\n| Date = October 5\n| Location = [[Bobby Dodd Stadium|Grant Field]]<br />[[Atlanta|Atlanta, GA]]\n| StartTime =\n| ElapsedTime =\n| Attendance =\n| Weather =\n| Referee =Lieut. Messer\n}}\n*'''Sources:'''<ref name=opening/><ref name=clem/>\n{{AFB game box end}}\nThe season opened with a 28\u20130 defeat of [[1918 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson]].  During the game, [[Red Barron]] hurdled tacklers for a 40-yard gain.<ref name=yearbp/> The last score came on a 55-yard run by [[Joe Guyon]].<ref name=clem>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5157735/the_charlotte_observer/|work=The Charlotte Observer|title=Georgia Tech Defeats Clemson College Team|page=16|date=October 6, 1918|accessdate=May 4, 2016|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref> Other scores came from Pug Allen and Wally Smith.<ref name=opening/> Former captain Everett Strupper cheered from the sidelines.<ref name=opening/>\n\nThe starting lineup was: Fincher (left end), Doyal (left tackle), Nesbit (left guard), Davis (center), Dowling (right guard), Vandegrift (right tackle), Staton (right end), Barron (quarterback), Ferst (left halfback), Guyon (right halfback), and Allen (fullback).<ref name=opening>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5174256/the_atlanta_constitution/|work=The Atlanta Constitution|title=Jackets Defeat Tigers In Typical Opening Game|page=3|author=Dick Jemison|date=October 6, 1918|accessdate=May 6, 2016|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\n===Furman===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Title = '''Furman at Georgia Tech'''\n| Visitor = Furman\n| Host = '''Ga. Tech'''\n| V1 = 0| V2 =0| V3 =0| V4 =0\n| H1 = 14| H2 =35| H3 =28| H4 =41\n| Date = October 12\n| Location = [[Bobby Dodd Stadium|Grant Field]]<br />[[Atlanta|Atlanta, GA]]\n| StartTime =\n| ElapsedTime =\n| Attendance =\n| Weather =\n| Referee =Lewis (Virginia)\n}}\n*'''Sources:'''<ref name=furm/>\n{{AFB game box end}}\nBuck Flowers starred in the 118\u20130 victory over [[1918 Furman Purple Hurricane football team|Furman]]. Joe Guyon played in the line and did well. Tech made 34 first downs.<ref name=furm>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5157616/the_atlanta_constitution/|author=[[Dick Jemison]]|title=Yellow Jackets Top Century Mark In Points Scored|work=Atlanta Constitution|page=3|date=October 13, 1918|accessdate=May 4, 2016|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref> For one score, in the fourth quarter, Flowers hit Red Barron on a 72-yard touchdown pass that went 42 yards in the air.<ref name=yearbp/>\n\nThe scoring breakdown: Barron got 4 touchdowns, Allen 3, Adams 2, Ferst 2, Guyon, Fincher, Flowers, Smith, Cobb, and Doyal one each. Fincher made 14 straight extra points.<ref name=yearbp/> Flowers made the other two.<ref name=furm/>\n\nThe starting lineup was: Fincher (left end), Doyal (left tackle), Rogers (left guard), Davis (center), Huffines (right guard), Guyon (right tackle), Staton (right end), Barron (quarterback), Flowers (left halfback), Ferst (right halfback), and Allen (fullback).<ref name=furm/>\n\n===11th Cavalry===\nTech beat the 11th Cavalry 123\u20130. The game was called after the start of the third quarter.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5157935/pittsburgh_postgazette/|work=The Gazette Times|location=Pittsburgh|title=Georgia Tech 123, 11 U. S. Cavalry 0|at=sec. 3, p. 4|accessdate=May 4, 2016|date=October 20, 1918}} {{Open access}}</ref> The scoring breakdown: Flowers  got 5 touchdowns, Barron 4, Ferst, Allen, and Staton 2 each, Smith, Fincher, and Cobb one each.<ref name=yearbp/>\n\n===Camp Gordon===\nGeorgia Tech beat [[1918 Camp Gordon football team|Camp Gordon]] 28\u20130. Frank Ferst and Red Barron each scored two touchdowns. \"Barron had the game of his life\" said the yearbook.<ref name=yearbp/>\n\nThe game was nip and tuck until Everett Strupper, former Tech star playing for Gordon, fumbled, and Ferst recovered, racing 30 yards for a touchdown. In the third quarter, Red Barron had a 28-yard touchdown.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5157909/the_tennessean/|work=The Tennessean|title=Georgia Tech Defeats Camp Gordon Eleven|date=October 27, 1918|page=24|accessdate=May 4, 2016|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\n===NC State===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Title = '''NC State at Georgia Tech'''\n| Visitor = NCST\n| Host = '''Ga. Tech'''\n| V1 = 0| V2 =0| V3 =0| V4 =0\n| H1 = 33| H2 =42| H3 =32| H4 =21\n| Date =November 9\n| Location = [[Bobby Dodd Stadium|Grant Field]]<br />[[Atlanta|Atlanta, GA]]\n| StartTime =\n| ElapsedTime =\n| Attendance =\n| Weather =\n| Referee =Moriarty\n}}\n*'''Sources:'''<ref name=armi/>\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nTwo days before the Armistice, Tech beat {{cfb link|year=1918|team=NC State Aggies|NC State}} 128\u20130. State's only highlight came in the third quarter, when [[John Ripple]] recovered a teammate's fumble and returned the ball 75 yards for a touchdown. However, it was called back due to an offsides penalty. [[Walter Camp]] attended the game. Ripple became the first football player from [[North Carolina]] ever to make an [[College Football All-America Team|All-America]] team when he was selected second-team All-American by Camp.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gopack.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/081108aac.html|title=The First Football All-American|author=Tim Peeler|accessdate=February 21, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221193044/http://www.gopack.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/081108aac.html|archivedate=February 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=campaa>{{cite news|title=Camp's All American: Football Dean Names Three Teams from Last Season's Records|work=The New York Times|date=December 31, 1918|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1918/12/31/97058136.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref> Five minutes into the fourth quarter, the game was called.<ref name=armi>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5162173/the_atlanta_constitution/|work=The Atlanta Constitution|date=November 10, 1918|page=3|title=Carolina Signs Armistice Before Game Is Concluded|author=[[Dick Jemison]]|accessdate=May 4, 2016|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref> The scoring breakdown: Barron and Ferst got 4 touchdowns each, Smith 3, Allen 3, Staton 2, Cobb 2, and Adams 1.<ref name=yearbp/><ref name=armi/>\n\nThe starting lineup was: Fincher (left end), Doyal (left tackle), Nesbit (left guard), Day (center), Rogers (right guard), Webb (right tackle), Staton (right end), Barron (quarterback), Ferst (left halfback), Adams (right halfback), and Allen (fullback).<ref name=armi/>\n\n===Pittsburgh===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Title = '''Georgia Tech at Pittsburgh'''\n| Visitor = Ga. Tech\n| Host = '''Pitt'''\n| V1 = 0| V2 =0| V3 =0| V4 =0\n| H1 = 7| H2 =7| H3 =12| H4 =6\n| Date =November 23\n| Location = [[Forbes Field]]<br />[[Pittsburgh, PA]]\n| StartTime =\n| ElapsedTime =\n| Attendance =30,000\n| Weather =\n| Referee =Tufts (Brown)\n}}\n*'''Sources:'''<ref name=open/>\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\nAfter declining the challenge the previous year, [[Glenn Scobey Warner|Pop Warner]]'s [[1918 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|Pittsburgh]] team was set to play Georgia Tech. In a high-profile game played as a War Charities benefit Pitt dismantled Georgia Tech 32\u20130, ending Tech's 33-game streak without a loss.<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Keck| first = Harry| title = Navy Reserves Steal Game From Pitt | journal = Pittsburgh Sunday Post | date = November 30, 1918 | page = 33 | publisher = Athlon Sports Communications | location=Nashville, TN | isbn = 1-878839-04-7}}. Republished in ''The Greatest Moments in Pitt Football History'' (1994).</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4LD1S47AQbcC&pg=PA3&source=bl&ots=zV3JBIPKJL&sig=BuvechMi6zMeE0YCocftaL_SRpk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjcpamD-8TMAhXLSSYKHTMiBJIQ6AEIODAE#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=50 Great Moments in Pittsburgh Sports: From the Flying Dutchman to Sid the Kid|author= David Shribman}}</ref> Pittsburgh was the 1918 national champion.<ref>{{Cite book| editor1-last=Borghetti| editor1-first=E.J.| editor2-last=Nestor| editor2-first=Mendy |editor3-last=Welsh| editor3-first=Celeste | title = 2008 Pitt Football Media Guide | publisher = University of Pittsburgh | year = 2008 | location = Pittsburgh, PA | page = 156 | url = http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/pitt/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2008FBMediaGuide.pdf| accessdate=2010-07-07}}</ref>\n[[File:DaviesPittGT1918.jpg|thumb|260px|Pitt's [[Tom Davies (American football)|Tom Davies]] runs against Tech.]]\nWarner historian Francis Powers wrote: \n<blockquote>At Forbes Field, the dressing rooms of the two teams were separated only by a thin wall. As the Panthers were sitting around, awaiting Warner's pre-game talk, Heisman began to orate in the adjoining room. In his charge to the Tech squad, Heisman became flowery and fiery. He brought the heroes of [[ancient Greece]] and the soldier dead in his armor among the ruins of [[Pompeii]]. It was terrific and the Panthers sat, spellbound. When Heisman had finished, Warner chortled and quietly said to his players: 'Okay, boys. There's the speech. Now go out and knock them off.'<ref>{{Harvnb|Powers|1969|page=42}}</ref>                                                            </blockquote>\n[[File:Joe Guyon 1918.gif|thumb|left|160px|Joe Guyon]]\nTech's play was early hindered by fumbles. One source relates \"Guyon and Flowers were very clever at intercepting forward passes, which in a measure made up for the fumbling in an early part of the game.\"<ref name=open/> Guyon also starred on defense.<ref name=yearbp/>\n\nPitt's first score came on a pass from [[Tom Davies (American football)|Tom Davies]] to [[Katy Easterday]].<ref name=open/> The next score came soon after the start of the second quarter, when Davies returned a punt back 50 yards for a touchdown. A double pass got the next score. The fourth touchdown was a 6-yard touchdown by [[George McLaren (American football)|George McLaren]].   A 55-yard touchdown run by Davies was the final score.<ref name=open>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5161961/the_tennessean/|work=The Tennessean|date=November 24, 1918|page=24|title=Panthers, With Open Attack Defeat Tech by 32 to 0 Score|accessdate=May 4, 2016|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\nPitt lost its only game to the Cleveland Naval Reserves. On the Naval team was former Tech star [[Judy Harlan]]. Harlan stated: \"I intercepted a pass and returned it to midfield in the fourth quarter. I felt I at least had evened up some of the losses we had at Tech.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/creatingbiggamej00umph|url-access=registration|title=Creating the Big Game: John W. Heisman and the Invention of American Football|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|author=Wiley Lee Umphlett|pages=[https://archive.org/details/creatingbiggamej00umph/page/148 148]|date=1992}}</ref>\n\nThe starting lineup was: Fincher (left end), Doyal (left tackle), Mathes (left guard), Day (center), Huffines (right guard), Webb (right tackle), Staton (right end), Barron (quarterback), Flowers (left halfback), Guyon (right halfback), and Allen (fullback).<ref name=open/>\n\n===Auburn===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Title = '''Auburn at Georgia Tech'''\n| Visitor = Auburn\n| Host = '''Ga. Tech'''\n| V1 = 0| V2 =0| V3 =0| V4 =0\n| H1 = 14| H2 =14| H3 =6| H4 =7\n| Date =November 28\n| Location = [[Bobby Dodd Stadium|Grant Field]]<br />[[Atlanta|Atlanta, GA]]\n| StartTime =\n| ElapsedTime =\n| Attendance =\n| Weather =\n| Referee = Lambert (Ohio State)\n}}\n*'''Sources:'''<ref name=aubie/>\n{{AFB game box end}}\nTech beat [[1918 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]] 41\u20130 on a muddy field. Substitute quarterback B. Adams returned a kickoff 80 yards for a touchdown. The other five touchdowns were achieved by plodding through the mud.<ref name=aubie>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4033359/the_tennessean/|title=Georgia Tech Using Forward Pass Often, Swamps Auburn, 41-0|work=The Tennessean|date=November 29, 1918|page=10|accessdate=January 13, 2016|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref> The first was on a pass from Buck Flowers to Joe Guyon. Flowers ran in the second, and Guyon ran in the third. Wally Smith made one, and Red Barron the last.<ref name=yearbp>[https://smartech.gatech.edu/handle/1853/14413 BluePrint, 1919]</ref>\n\nThe starting lineup: was Fincher (left end), Doyal (left tackle), Webb (left guard), Day (center), Mathes (right guard), Huffines (right tackle), Staton (right end), Barron (quarterback), Flowers (left halfback), Ferst (right halfback), and Guyon (fullback).<ref name=aubie/>\n\n===University of Pennsylvania===\nGeorgia Tech had a scheduled game with the [[1918 Penn Quakers football team|University of Pennsylvania]] in Philadelphia canceled when   the [[Spanish flu]] swept thrpugh Philadelphia.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fitzpatrick |first=Frank|date=March 11, 2020|title=In 1918, it was Spanish influenza that afflicted Philadelphia sports |url=https://www.inquirer.com/health/coronavirus/philadelphia-1918-spanish-influenza-penn-quakers-football-20200311.html |work=Philadelphia Inquirer |location=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Postseason==\n===Awards and honors===\n[[File:BumDay.jpg|thumb|200px|Bum Day]]\n[[Center (gridiron football)|Center]] [[Bum Day]] was recognized as a consensus first-team [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]]. He was a first-team selection by Walter Camp.<ref>''[http://issuu.com/gtathletics/docs/2013_georgia_tech_football_media_gu?e=1285467/4129206#search  2013 Georgia Tech Football Information Guide]'', Georgia Tech Athletic Association, Atlanta, Georgia, pp. 170, 178, 180 (2013).  Retrieved August 20, 2014.</ref><ref name=awards>''2014 NCAA Football Records Book'', [https://web.archive.org/web/20141222163944/http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/football_records/2014/Awards.pdf  Award Winners], National Collegiate Athletic Association, Indianapolis, Indiana, pp. 2, 4, 14 (2014).  Retrieved August 20, 2014.</ref>  Day's selection by Camp as a first-team All-American was a historic first; he was the first [[Southern United States|Southerner]] to be chosen for Camp's annual All-America first team, which had been historically loaded with college players from [[Harvard Crimson football|Harvard]], [[Yale Bulldogs football|Yale]], [[Princeton Tigers football|Princeton]], and other [[American Northeast|Northeastern]] colleges.<ref>Joe Williams, \"Joe Williams Says,\" ''El Paso Herald-Post'', p. 10 (November 12, 1935).  Retrieved August 20, 2014.</ref> [[Captain (sports)|Captain]] Bill Fincher was also a consensus All-American, as well as Joe Guyon.<ref name=awards/> Fincher and [[Halfback (American football)|halfback]] Buck Flowers made Camp's second-team All-American.<ref name=campaa/>\n\n===Championships===\nTech won its fourth straight SIAA title.<ref>{{Harvnb|Woodruff|1928|page=71}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n===Depth chart===\nThe following chart provides a visual depiction of Tech's lineup during the 1918 season with games started at the position reflected in parenthesis. The chart mimics the offense after the [[jump shift]] has taken place.\n{|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n\n  {| style=\"width:100%\"\n  | align=\"left\" |\n  \n    {| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n    ! [[End (American football)|LE]]\n    |- \n    |[[Bill Fincher]] (6)\n   |-\n  |&nbsp;\n |-\n  |&nbsp;\n |-\n  |&nbsp;\n    |}\n  \n  |\n  \n    {| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n    ! [[Offensive Tackle|LT]] !! [[Guard (American football)|LG]] !! [[Center (American football)|C]] !! [[Guard (American football)|RG]] !! [[Offensive Tackle|RT]]\n    |-\n    |Shorty Doyal (5)||M. M. Nesbit (2)|| [[Bum Day]] (3)|| R. D. Huffines (2)|| B. P. Webb (2)\n    |-\n    |||W. T. Mathis (1)||[[Oscar Davis (American football)|Oscar Davis]] (2) ||[[Ham Dowling]] (1)||[[Joe Guyon]] (1)\n   |-\n   |||J. C. Rogers (1) || ||W. T. Mathis (1)||R. D. Huffines (1)\n|-\n|| ||B. P. Webb (1)|| ||J. C. Rogers (1) ||Vandegrift (1)\n    |}\n  | \n  {| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n    ! [[End (American football)|RE]]\n    |-\n    |[[Albert Staton]] (6)\n   |-\n  |&nbsp;\n |-\n  |&nbsp;\n|-\n  |&nbsp;\n    |}\n  \n  |-\n  |\n  | align=\"right\" |\n  \n    {| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n    ! [[Quarterback|QB]]\n    |- \n    | [[Red Barron]] (7)\n   |-\n   |B. Adams (0)\n    |}\n |-\n |\n  | align=\"right\" |\n    {| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n    ! [[Halfback (American football)|RHB]]\n    |- \n    | Frank Ferst (3)\n|-\n|Joe Guyon (2)\n|-\